[37m[1mKeep secrets of the implementation.[0m[0m[37m Secrets are assumptions about an implementation that client programs are not allowed to make. In other words, they are things that can change; the interface defines the things that cannot change (without simultaneous changes to both implementation and client). Obviously, it is easier to program and modify a system if its parts make fewer assumptions about each other. On the other hand, the system may not be easier to design - it's hard to design a good interface. And there is a tension with the desire not to hide power.[0m[30m[1m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m[0m
[37m[1mOne way to improve performance is to increase the number of assumptions that one part of a system makes about another[0m[0m[37m; the additional assumptions often allow less work to be done, sometimes a lot less. For instance, if a set of size [0m[37m[1mn[0m[0m[37m is known to be sorted, a membership test takes time [0m[37m[1mlog n[0m[0m[37m rather than [0m[37m[1mn[0m[0m[37m. This technique is very important in the design of algorithms and the tuning of small modules. In a large system the ability to improve each part separately is usually more important. Striking the right balance remains an art.[0m[30m[1m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m[0m
[37m[1mDivide and conquer.[0m[0m[37m A well known method for solving a hard problem: reduce it to several easier ones. The resulting program is usually recursive. When resources are limited the method takes a slightly different form: bite off as much as will fit, leaving the rest for another iteration.[0m[30m[1m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m[0m
