[37m[1mSafety first.[0m[0m[37m In allocating resources, [0m[37m[1mstrive to avoid disaster rather than to attain an optimum[0m[0m[37m. Many years of experience with virtual memory, networks, disk allocation, database layout, and other resource allocation problems has made it clear that a general-purpose system cannot optimize the use of resources.[0m[30m[1m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m[0m
[37m[1mShed load to control demand, rather than allowing the system to become overloaded.[0m[0m[37m There are many ways to shed load. An interactive system can refuse new users, or even deny service to existing ones. A memory manager can limit the jobs being served so that all their working sets fit in the available memory. A network can discard packets. If it comes to the worst, the system can crash and start over more prudently.[0m[30m[1m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m[0m
